<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Why does altitude affect canning?", answer: "Water boils at a lower temperature at higher altitudes because atmospheric pressure decreases. At sea level, water boils at 212 degrees F, but at 5,000 feet it boils at about 203 degrees F. This lower temperature means bacteria and spores are not killed as effectively, so processing times or pressures must be increased." },
  { question: "How much extra time do I add for water bath canning at altitude?", answer: "Per USDA guidelines: add 5 minutes at 1,001-3,000 feet, 10 minutes at 3,001-6,000 feet, 15 minutes at 6,001-8,000 feet, and 20 minutes at 8,001-10,000 feet above sea level." },
  { question: "How does altitude affect pressure canning?", answer: "For dial gauge canners, increase pressure by 1 PSI for every 2,000 feet above 1,000 feet. For weighted gauge canners, simply use 15 PSI instead of 10 PSI at any altitude above 1,000 feet." },
  { question: "Can I use a water bath canner for low-acid foods?", answer: "No. Low-acid foods (vegetables, meats, poultry, seafood) must be processed in a pressure canner to reach 240 degrees F, which destroys Clostridium botulinum spores. Water bath canning only reaches the boiling point and is safe only for high-acid foods like fruits, pickles, and jams." },
  { question: "How do I find my altitude?", answer: "Search for your city or zip code followed by 'elevation' in any search engine. You can also use GPS-enabled smartphone apps or check topographic maps. Many county extension offices also provide local altitude information." }
]) %>

